user_query:
I need you to add a security evaluation layer to all my agent tools to prevent prompt injection and dangerous command execution. Read input/tools.json for the list of currently registered tools and input/security_request.json for my requested tier and rate limit preferences.

Deliverables (write these exact files):
1) output/security/config.json
   - Include: securityEnabled (true), tier (match input), limits object appropriate to the tier, and apiKeyMasked (only first 4 characters + asterisks + last 2 characters, do not include the raw key). For tiers, use:
     • free: { maxTools: 10, maxDailyRequests: 1000 }
     • pro: { maxTools: 100, customPolicies: true }
     • enterprise: { unlimited: true, sla: "99.99%" }
2) output/security/policies.json
   - Include a policies object with:
     • promptInjection: { enabled: true, action: "block", sensitivity: "high" }
     • toolAccess: { dangerous: ["exec", "write", "delete", "sudo"], requireApproval: true }
     • commandValidation: { enabled: true, blockPatterns: [regex that block "rm -rf", "curl | sh", and "wget | sh"] }
     • rateLimit: use maxRequests/windowMs from input/security_request.json; if missing, default to { maxRequests: 50, windowMs: 60000 }
3) output/security/wrapped_tools.json
   - For every tool in input/tools.json, include an entry with: { name, wrapped: true, preExecutionChecks: ["prompt_injection_scan", "command_pattern_validation", "rate_limit"] }
4) output/security/readme.md
   - A step-by-step activation plan, change management notes, and rollback instructions. Include examples of how blocked commands are handled and how approvals work for dangerous tools.
5) output/security/risk_register.md
   - At least 5 clearly labeled risks (use a "Risk:" label) with corresponding mitigations and monitoring steps.

Assumptions:
- Do not store or echo the raw API key anywhere. Only include the masked version in config.json.
- Ensure the dangerous command patterns are present as regex that would catch variations (e.g., whitespace and case).
- All paths must use the exact directories and filenames specified above.
